revision.text:
'''Ahmad ibn al-Tayyib al-Sarakhsi''' ({{lang-ar|أحمد بن الطيب السرخسي}}; died 899 CE) was a [[Persian peoples|Persian]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Frye|first1=ed. by R.N.|title=The Cambridge history of Iran.|date=1975|publisher=Cambridge U.P.|location=London|isbn=978-0-521-20093-6|page=415|edition=Repr.|quote=The physicians of the caliphs continued to be Christians and Jews until the time of the caliph al-Muctadid who had a Persian Muslim physician, Ahmad b. al-Tayyib al-Sarakhsl.}}</ref> traveler, historian and philosopher from the city of [[Sarakhs]]. He was a pupil of [[al-Kindi]].<ref>{{cite book|last=F. E.|first=Peters|title=Aristotle and the Arabs: The Aristotelian Tradition in Islam|year=1968|publisher=[[New York University Press]]|page=159}}</ref>
Al-Sarakhsi was killed by Caliph [[al-Mu'tadid]] because, according to an anecdote preserved in [[Yaqut al-Hamawi]]'s ''Mu'jam al-Udaba''', he had urged the caliph towards apostasy. [[Al-Biruni]] reports in his ''Chronology'' that al-Sarakhsi had written books in which he denounced prophecy and ridiculed the prophets, whom he styled charlatans. However, Rosenthal has disputed the historicity of the stories that claim al-Sarakhsi was executed for heretical beliefs.<ref>{{cite book|last=McKinney|first=Robert C.|title=The case of rhyme versus reason: Ibn al-Rūmī and his poetics in context|year=2004|publisher=Brill|location=Leiden|isbn=90-04-13010-1|page=27}}</ref>
