The '''Conseil Souverain of Navarre and Béarn''' (French: ''"Conseil Souverain de Navarre et de Béarn"'', alias ''"Conseil Souverain de Navarre"'' and ''"Conseil Souverain de Béarn"'') was created by [[Henry II of Navarre]]<ref name="Laussat (1871), p. 166">Laussat (1871), p. 166 [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k34253p/f176.item.zoom (in French)]</ref> at the [[Château de Pau]]<ref name="Laussat (1871), p. 166" /> on {{date|13 June 1519}},<ref name="Laussat (1871), p. 166" /> replacing the [[Cour Majour]] which was disbanded in {{date|1490}}.
It functioned as a ''Conseil d'État'' and was composed of counsellors ''(French: conseillers)'', a prosecutor general ''(French: procureur général)'', a criminal prosecutor ''(French: procureur criminel)'', an attorney general ''(French: avocat général)'', several second presidents ''(French: second présidents)'' and one first president ''(French: premier président)''. These offices were essentially bought and sold, often passed down during generations within the same families. The purchase, sale or transfer of the office required the ratification of the [[Chambre des Comptes of Navarre]] in [[Pau, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Pau]], who acted on behalf of the king.
In October<ref name="Saget (1831)">{{cite book|author=P. Saget|title=Description du château de Pau et de ses dépendances|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z_j25dmOSVQC&pg=PA46|year=1831|publisher=E. Vignancour|page=46}}</ref> {{date|1620}}, together with the [[Chancery of Navarre]] based in [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]], it was merged to form the [[Parliament of Navarre and Béarn]] ''("Parlement de Navarre et Béarn")'' in [[Pau, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Pau]],<ref name="Guyot (1784)">{{cite book|author=M. Guyot (Joseph Nicolas)|title=Répertoire universel et raisonné de jurisprudence civile, criminelle, canonique et béneficiale: ouvrage de plusieurs jurisconsultes: mis en ordre & publié|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iW5GAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA592|year=1784|publisher=Visse|page=592}}</ref> after which it was renamed to the '''Conseil d'État de Navarre'''.
The registers of the ''Conseil Souverain of Navarre and Béarn'' for the period {{date|1547}} until {{date|1620}} are held ''Archives Départementales des Pyrénées-Atlantiques'' in [[Pau, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Pau]].
