{{Infobox person | name = Edvard Beyer | image = Edvard Beyer.jpg | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1920|10|6|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Haugesund]], Norway | death_date = {{Death date and age|2003|11|10|1920|10|6|df=y}} | death_place = [[Bærum ]] | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} --> | monuments = | residence = | nationality = Norwegian | other_names = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Literary historian | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | television = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives= | parents = [[Harald Beyer (literary historian)|Harald Beyer]] | awards = [[Fritt Ord Honorary Award]] }}
'''Edvard Freydar Beyer''' (6 October 1920 &ndash; 10 November 2003) was a Norwegian [[literary history|literary historian]], [[literary critic]], and professor at the [[University of Oslo]] from 1958 to 1990.
==Early and personal life== Beyer was born in [[Haugesund]] and grew up in [[Bergen]], as a son of literary historian, later professor [[Harald Beyer (literary historian)|Harald Beyer]] (1891&ndash;1960), and Eidis Johannessen (1893&ndash;1977). He was married to nurse Aslaug Ryssdal from 1946.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Edvard Beyer |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|first=Atle |last=Kittang|authorlink=Atle Kittang|year=1999|volume=1|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Edvard_Beyer/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=10 April 2009}}</ref>
==Career== Beyer studied [[philology]], and graduated with the dissertation ''Livsgleden som problem i Ibsens diktning'', which was published in the journal ''[[Edda. Scandinavian Journal of Literary Research|Edda]]'' in 1948. The next ten years he worked as an independent literary critic for [[Bergens Tidende]], and eventually as a lecturer at the [[University of Bergen]].<ref name=nbl/> He took his [[dr.philos.]] degree in 1956, with the thesis ''Hans E. Kinck; livsangst og livstro'' (about [[Hans E. Kinck]], issued in two volumes, in 1956 and 1965). His doctorate thesis is regarded as his most important research work.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=Edvard Freydar Beyer|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor=Henriksen, Petter |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Edvard_Freydar_Beyer |language=Norwegian | accessdate=10 April 2009 }}</ref> It is regarded as one of the most voluminous monographies on a poet in Norway.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edvard Beyer (obituary)|last=Nettum|first=Rolf Nyboe|authorlink=Rolf Nyboe Nettum|date=25 November 2003|work=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref>
Beyer was appointed professor in [[Nordic literature]] at the [[University of Oslo]] in 1958, succeeding [[Francis Bull]]. He also took over Bull's position as editor-in-chief of ''Edda'', from 1962 to 1972. He was main editor for ''Norges litteraturhistorie'' (six volumes, 1974&ndash;1975), where he also wrote volume three and part of volume two, on literature from the 1800s. He was the Norwegian editor for the Scandinavian project ''Verdens litteraturhistorie'' (twelve volumes, 1971&ndash;1974). During the 1980s Beyer administered and contributed to the project ''Norsk litteraturkritikks historie 1770–1940'', the history of Norwegian literary criticism from 1770 to 1940. He edited the collected works of Hans E. Kinck (18 volumes), and the short story anthologies ''Perler i prosa'' (1966) and ''Norske noveller'' (1967).<ref name=nbl/>
Beyer was chairman of [[Arts Council Norway]] from 1978 to 1985. He was a member of the [[Norwegian Academy of Science and Letters]] from 1959. He retired as a professor in 1990.<ref name=snl/> In the same year he received the [[Fritt Ord Honorary Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fritt-ord.no/no/priser/category/fritt_ords_honnor/|title=Priser – Fritt Ords Honnør|publisher=[[Fritt Ord (organization)|Fritt Ord]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref> He died in November 2003 in [[Bærum]].<ref name=nbl/>
